28-year-old chef found dead in San Francisco mall
The 28-year-old chef, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in a stairwell at a local mall this week.
However, the victim's brother says he can't imagine anyone wanting to hurt him, noting, "Finally, things were going well for him."
"The body found in Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning was identified as 28-year-old San Francisco resident Frank Galizia," the San Francisco Forensic Bureau said in a statement.
The San Francisco Police Department reports that the death was classified as a homicide and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim’s brother, Luis Galizia, told San Francisco-based ABC’s KGO that Frank, a former Boston line chef, got his dream job as a cook at San Francisco’s Sons & Daughters six months ago.
A spokesman for Sons & Daughters said they were "shocked and depressed" by his death.
“We are a small team that works as a close-knit family and will be greatly missed,” the spokesman said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank’s family and friends during this difficult time.
Luis Galicia said that Frank first stayed in hostels, but recently "Finally, things were going well for him."
“He found an apartment, he was dating a girl,” Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said he couldn’t imagine anyone wanting to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good soul and a big heart.
His way of communicating with his family has always been to cook us some dish, to cook us dinner,” said Luis Galicia.
He never wanted to be involved in a fight.
He was a brother who was floating.
“With all the bad things that are happening to this world, it was that uncut diamond that shone brightly every day,” he said.
Anyone with information is asked to call the SFPD Hotline at 415-575-4444.
