Vinyl End User: Who Really Buys Vinyl?
Lonely middle-aged men love vinyl.
And as long as you do not rush to clutter the comment section with gross insults under the pseudonym Non-Single Men of the Middle Years, this statement follows from the factual data.
According to YouGov, the much-discussed revival of records is due not to the boom among the generation of 2,000, who want to imbue themselves with the novelty of a material object, but to the nostalgia of middle age.
Those who have recently purchased a vinyl album are more likely to be between the ages of 45 and 54, according to the data.
Moreover, those who belong to the age group of 18-24 years are the least likely.
It’s also not just the act of collecting amateurs – it has an emotional meaning: older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to keep their feelings to themselves (56% vs. 53%) and enjoy loneliness (69% vs. 66%).
But are the results of YouGov true?
If this blog were a television news report, the camera would follow me as I walked down the center of the bustling Soho street, in a modest gray suit and violently gestured before a stop, folding my arms and saying something impressive like, "Well, let's see."
All right, let's see.
While the heart of the Soho is slowly losing its charm and dirt — hotels, cafes, Paperchase stores are now flooding buildings once occupied by independent sellers — a few music stores with fantastic specialists are still left.
I’d probably ask the camera to stop for the next scene where I’m close to different people in some of these stores and trying to gauge their age and emotional state of mind through observation.
Glasgow native Stewart, 55 years old, whom I followed from Sister Ray (counting data: two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (counting data: eight middle-aged men, one woman probably over 20), in London for a half-day to hold a meeting, and strolling around the shops to take a few hours.
He's a collector, I ask?
“I guess so,” he says.
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records.
These records, pictured above (he emailed me a picture, I didn’t follow him home), run in lines along the walls of his living room.
His reason for buying so many albums and singles comes in part from his disposable income: he can now buy records he couldn’t afford when they first came out and buy back items he sold when he was young and broke.
“A lot of what I buy is the late '60s, the early '70s, things that came out when I was 11 or 12, things that I was probably too young to buy,” he says.
He agrees that those who buy the records are most likely introverts who like their own company, adding: “I don’t smoke, I don’t drink too much.
That's my flaw.
Wez, 25, who works for Sister Ray, also believes that many of the clients he meets fit the YouGov profile.
He, however, noticed a new wave of people being influenced by the hype in the media, people who heard about the return and felt the obligation to buy back their old records.
Judging by the conversations I had, people got rid of their collection, usually around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who once sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy back their records,” he says.
This may explain the boom among vinyl revival figures of a certain age.
What about the supposed emotional importance of the records?
It is enough to spend a few seconds in a store like Phonica to realize that record stores offer a comfortable society to people with similar views.
According to Ouez, some older customers, in particular, are insulted by the cashless payment system.
Some vinyl lovers may feel shaken by the digital world and prefer to retreat to the permanence of familiar record envelopes, items that evoke memories of serene youth.
“I think sometimes it can be filling in a void or possessing material things as a kind of soothing,” says Wes.
Since I’m a collector myself, I have it, and I think a lot of people have it too.
It’s an easy way to keep your head occupied.
"We are like their social workers!" - said a colleague from the shelf of records.
An ICM survey in April found that nearly 50 percent of people who bought a vinyl album last month hadn’t listened to it yet.
The survey also found that 41% had a record player that they never used, while 7% of those who bought vinyl had no record player.
At this stage of the news report, I would probably look seriously puzzled, sliding through the rack with the collections of Bosanów.
The "trophy" aspect of the revival is what Johnny, 42, who works at Sounds of the Universe noticed.
“Someone came in recently and said, ‘I don’t have a record player, but I want to buy a Radiohead record so we can put it on my shelf,’” he says.
It’s not a big percentage, but it definitely happens.
More music, less music.
We have people who say, "I don't have a record player."
These are younger people, not older, they are a little under twenty, who are just getting acquainted with this.
Fopp, who has now taken almost the entire vinyl floor, has a much more diverse audience when I arrive.
There are couples over 70, tourists who take photos, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
Although the atmosphere is less laid-back than in the aforementioned stores – the latest synth and sexy Wild Beast pop, rather than jazz improvisation, breaks through the speakers – it’s nice to see the diversity in your customers.
None of them look particularly lonely, but the excruciating psychological trauma is hard to establish by standing next to someone for 30 seconds.
Eleanor, 27, walked Fopp for a few minutes, looking at the various records on sale.
She looks at the goods, not spends the money.
She doesn’t earn much, she says, so collecting records isn’t a very good option.
It's expensive.
Listening to music on a computer or other device is simple, but the beauty of vinyl is ..." - she immerses herself in dreams with a sigh of love.
I don't know how to explain it - it's really unique.
My last stop is a store that is said to have contributed to the emergence of a new generation of vinyl lovers: Urban Fashionistas.
While I create the illusion that I’m looking at denim-framed shorts, I’m watching a group of teenage girls gather around the Polaroid camera every minute before a father and his daughter start discussing the purchase of a Crosley player.
On the left is a staircase with Adele, Jeff Buckley, Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mac plates: a mix of modern style and classics, a must-have for any medium-sized collection.
No one is looking—perhaps because they are just decorations, some so high up on the wall that it would be impossible to touch them.
It's a real "artistic vinyl."
But, given that any attention to these items could mean more money for the industry and send a few customers to the Soho backlands for a while longer, there’s almost nothing to complain about.
Not surprisingly, the stratum of the population that is more likely than most to have more time and money than most is the stratum that spends most of the money on luxury items such as vinyl.
But while my findings suggest that YouGov’s results are accurate, at least in Soho record stores, they don’t rule out the existence of a huge number of female collectors and vinyl lovers that exist in reality, in record stores and on online forums.
These people probably work all the time in school or offices.
But they clearly don’t spend the morning of Thursday strolling around Berwick Street’s record shops, scrolling through records and avoiding the gaze of an unpleasant 30-year-old fake presenter who hangs over the shoulders of unsuspecting middle-aged men.
