They said that home-made shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to expel the people who run the 72 home-made stores, but said Calais Prefecture's problems were "completely understandable."
Judge Jean-François Molla said grocery stores, cafes and restaurants played a much bigger role than just feeding people who “live in extremely shaky conditions.”
He said the spaces provided quiet meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One place that was in danger of being demolished was the children’s cafe Jungle Book at the camp, which works not for profit and offers 200 lunches a day, English and French classes, and asylum counselling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
More than 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children’s cafe.
The letter, sent to the Guardian, said its closure "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are no more than eight years old."
Two charities, Refugee Aid and L'Auberge des Migrants, estimated on Friday that the number at Camp Jungle had risen to more than 9,000 people — the highest ever — after a sharp increase in new arrivals during the summer.
