Helen Glover and Heather Stanning Inspired to Win Rowing by Coach’s Fight Against Cancer
There will be no more exciting gold at these games, and that says something.
From the first movement to the last, 220 heavy lifts in history, Helen Glover and Heather Stanning have found the added value of their golden moment at the Estacio da Lagoa.
Although they were the two that pulled the oars, there were three voices in this boat, the echo of coach Robin Williams was always there as they sought the second consecutive Olympic gold in female pairs, the first women in the annals of British sport to reach such a height.
Their superiority was absolute, after all it was their 39th unbeaten performance, once again unprecedented.
What we see, two brilliant female athletes, sliding on the surface with the elegance of swans, do not fully reflect the nature of triumph.
Behind every gold rowed a battalion of ready-made hands contributing to the gradually increasing victories that matter, and there are no hands that were more important than the hands of the coach, who 30 months ago, when he was diagnosed with cancer, did not know whether he would live to see that day.
Like he said, it was a dangerous business.
I had bladder cancer, which is one that they can operate on, and they did.
If they don’t, they go everywhere.
It could have been a pretty bad situation.
It changes your vision for the future.
Williams was diagnosed in December 2013.
The trio are fortunate to have been able to start treatment in early 2014 off-season, keeping the schedule gap minimal if that may be the correct expression in circumstances like these.
I needed to pay, so I needed to get better quickly.
It was an incentive.
I was in the hospital and walking through the ward — 20 feet, 30 feet, 50 feet at a time, although they said there were enough few steps.
That's how it starts.
Rowing itself is a journey, but it makes it a little bit bigger.
The moment after the victory, their first thoughts were about Williams, who spent a nervous morning talking a little more than usual in an attempt to overcome his own experiences.
Stanning, captain of an artillery regiment with service in Afghanistan behind her shoulders, said: “I’ve been an emotional wreck this week, maybe it’s a bit over the top, but it means so much.”
It just confirms how much it means to me, how much Helen and I have worked, and Robin too.
It’s been a fantastic three years with Helen and Robin.
Without Robin, we would be nothing, so thank you very much, he is the best coach in the world.
I couldn’t ask for a better coach or a better coach.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning have not lost a single race in five years.
This pair sets a tense rhythm that their competitors could never match.
Even on the last 500 meters, when the teams of New Zealand and Denmark began to approach, Stanning and Glover had too much in reserve.
We were very much in phase.
Helen said, "Stay in the process, stay in the process."
It is very important not to get carried away.
We had a good start and at the same time we weren’t trying to do anything amazing.
We weren’t expecting fireworks today, we were just expecting to be able to row well and go out and win this race, which we did.
It will take a year for the couple to decide their future.
Glover is due to be at a wedding next month, on her own, with television adventurer Steve Backshall.
She just wants to enjoy the moment.
I didn’t want to say this was my last race.
