The UN is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
A UN special commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but the UN special envoy for Syria Steffan de Mistura believes the fact of what happened is undeniable.
Such statements were made on the eve of the third round of intra-Syrian talks, which should begin in late August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of chemical weapons use in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the attack with the use of toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where the Russian military transport helicopter was shot down the day before, the aircraft dropped bombs with a poisonous substance, but in Moscow, these accusations were called a drop.
Later, the Russian Defense Ministry accused the opposition group “Harakyat Nur al-Din al-Zinki” of the incident.
Soon it became known that there were two bombs filled with toxic gas.
This was confirmed by the BBC by one of the victims.
“A few minutes later, I smelled gas, my eyes began to burn, it became difficult to breathe,” he said.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people died, 23 were hospitalized.
If the use of poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be considered a war crime.
UN special envoy for Syria Staffan de Mistura told reporters: “There is a lot of evidence that this really happened.”
The prohibition of the use of chlorine for military purposes is stipulated in the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015 human rights activists recorded 35 cases of the use of chlorine by the Syrian army against the “moderate opposition”.
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that shelling of its areas is carried out daily, and terrorists are preventing the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects Russia to establish a “humanitarian pause” in military action.
The current regime of daily three-hour silence in the organization is considered "insufficient to help the almost 2 million civilians trapped."
Staffan de Mistura's humanitarian adviser, Jan Egeland, said a 48-hour ceasefire would be required every week to get help and evacuate sick and wounded from the city.
"We have to send bulk cargoes from a convoy of trucks in areas where the roads are practically destroyed, and those that remain are mined," Mr. Egeland said. - But the Russian delegation confirmed its readiness to sit down with us at the negotiating table."
Consultations in Geneva between the representatives of the United States and Russia on the establishment of a “humanitarian pause” continue.
How Russia opened “humanitarian windows” in Aleppo.
In the face of the ongoing battle for Aleppo, Syria’s second-largest city, Russia announced on August 11 a three-hour ceasefire that will be in effect daily from Thursday.
The creation of “humanitarian windows” is designed to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and basic necessities to the city.
The decision of the Ministry of Defense of the Russian Federation was taken against the backdrop of increasing international pressure on Moscow with the demand to terminate the military operation and facilitate the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions in the resorts of Thailand killed four people.
Several explosions occurred in southern Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed and 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, Russians are not among them.
No terrorist group has yet claimed responsibility for the incident, but the country’s interior ministry hastened to say that Islamists are not involved.
Several people have already been arrested on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data from the local police, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military leaders of the country.
The attacks occurred at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the Phuket area and the cities of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the military junta came to power in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries to show development.
In 2016, 14 million people visited the country, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of the attacks have already been detained, police colonel Krisana Patanacharoen said.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the Ministry of Internal Affairs of the country is "confident that they are not associated with international extremist groups."
“It’s too early to draw conclusions,” Mr. Patanacharoen said.
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact, they are local sabotage, and we are trying to identify the identities of those behind them.
The blasts occurred on the birthday of Queen Sikrit of Thailand.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy one of its top priorities, so the incident is most likely directed against it.
According to Police General Sithichai Srisopacharoenrat, the bombs were detonated remotely with a half-hour difference.
They were hidden inside trees in busy streets filled with dining tourists in restaurants.
One of the four dead was a Thai girl who sold street food.
The identity of the other victims is not yet known, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign states.
According to the Royal Thai Police, among them are four German citizens, three Dutch citizens, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service of Rosturizm reported.
Local experts also link the explosions to the August 7 referendum, in which 61.4% of the country’s population supported the draft new constitution.
It was prepared by a commission to draft a constitution appointed by the military junta.
Voters had to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and played a significant role in electing the country's prime minister.
The new system was adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
Recall that on May 22, 2014 in Thailand there was a military coup under the leadership of the commander of the army of the country Prayuth Chan-Ocha.
The move, he said, was prompted by an ongoing political crisis and a lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, imposed curfews and censorship, dispersed the protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok was in a state of emergency
The government of Thailand, led by Prime Minister Yinglak Shinawatra, declared a state of emergency in Bangkok and the surrounding provinces in January 2014.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
There were two explosions in Bangkok.
In January 2014, two explosions occurred in central Bangkok near the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, injuring 28 people, five of whom were in critical condition.
The explosions were carried out by unknown people on motorcycles.
Authorities have stepped up security in the capital and mobilized military forces to protect the demonstrators.
In Sukhy Log, the development of conditions began.
As it became known to Kommersant, the government was invited to agree on the draft terms of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold field with the preservation of two key restrictions.
It is proposed not to allow the auction company, where 25% or more belongs to foreigners, and those applicants in the capital of which will not be at least 25% of the state.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewrite the terms, noting that many players already do not risk taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources submitted to the government a draft order and conditions for the auction of the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two sources familiar with the situation told Kommersant.
The project was submitted on Wednesday evening, one of them clarifies.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed "Kommersant" that the project was submitted to the government.
A representative of Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin, who oversees subsoil use, told Kommersant that the project has not yet entered the office of the official.
"The auction can be announced in August, immediately after the government order is issued, and taking into account the deadline for collecting applications from potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender can be held in October," the Ministry of Natural Resources said.
According to Kommersant, the project retained two key requirements for potential participants, prescribed in the version that was sent for approval to the ministries and the FOIV in July (Komersant has it).
The first is the presence in the capital of applicants of at least 25% state ownership.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies under the control of foreign investors, based on the understanding of FZ-57 about foreign investments in strategic companies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law, as already written by Kommersant on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship may not be allowed to the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, since the Sukhoi Log belongs to the subsoil of federal importance (stocks of more than 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project "contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies", but declined to comment on the details before the order of the government.
The demand for state participation in the capital of the auction participants was put forward by the Irkutsk region, said in December 2015 "Kommersant" in the Ministry of Natural Resources and later confirmed by the Governor of the region Sergey Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources his predecessor Sergey Eroshchenko, "had agreements on investment projects" Ro.
Who lobbied for the restriction on the admission of foreigners, the interlocutors of "Kommersant" do not specify.
“But it’s in the spirit of the time: not to give up control of the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions,” says Kommersant, who is familiar with the preparation of the auction.
On August 1, the head of the Ministry of Natural Resources, Sergey Donskoy, said that foreigners “can go to the consortium” if the applicants attract them “as a financial structure, technological partners”.
The interlocutors of "Kommersant" believe it is unlikely that the government will adjust the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is considered a consortium of the largest gold miner of the Russian Federation, PJSC "Polyus", controlled by the son of Suleiman Kerimov Said, and Rostec.
According to Kommersant, in July, the partners created the joint venture "SL Gold", where "Polyus" 51% shares, the structure of "Rostekh" RT-GR - 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, Poljus said Kommersant was "unquestionably interested in this asset" and had all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
"But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the announcement of the conditions," the Pole added.
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision is for the government of the Russian Federation, Kommersant sources said.
The possibility of participation in the development of the Sukhoi Log was claimed by Russian GV Gold and Canadian Kinross, which develops assets in Chukotka, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
The head of the Union of gold producers of the Russian Federation Sergey Kashuba in December 2015 estimated Kommersant's investments in Sukhoi Log at $2.5-4 billion.
Most potential applicants are discouraged not only by the volume of investment, but also by the complexity of the project: serious exploration of reserves and technology for working with complex ores is needed, Kommersant’s interlocutors in the industry explain.
In the pension market launched the largest M&A transaction - "KIT Finance Pension Administrator" launched the process of merging four controlled NPFs.
As a result, on the basis of the "Gazfond Pension Savings" will be created NPF with a savings volume of about 373 billion rubles.
The launch of the procedure for merging four pension funds - "KIT Finance", "Promagrofond", "Heritage" and "Gazfond Pension savings" - was announced yesterday by the owner of 100% of funds of LLC "KIT Finance Pension Administrator".
“The reorganization is carried out in coordination with the Central Bank, subject to the requirement of non-deterioration of the terms of the existing contracts,” the company said in a statement.
The merger is carried out on the basis of Gazfond Pension Savings.
As noted by the Director General of this NPF Oleg Bialoshitsky, the unification of funds allows solving several problems: expanding the geography of the presence, concentrating resources for development, reducing costs, replicating the best practices of each of the funds and optimizing corporate governance.
According to him, the approximate deadline for the completion of the consolidation is the second quarter of 2017.
As a result of the merger, Gazfond Pension Savings will become the largest player in the OPS market.
As of March 31, the volume of pension savings of the pooling funds exceeded 373 billion rubles.
As follows from the reports on the website of the funds, the beneficiaries of their owner - "KIT Finance Pension Administrator" - are currently Anatoly Gavrilenko (through controlled LLC owns 65%) and NPF "Gazfond" (35%).
However, the merger itself launched the group much later than competitors.
So, under the control of group O1 NPF "Future" absorbed "Stalfond" at the beginning of this year.
Currently, this combined NPF joins the Uralsib and Russian Standard foundations.
“Unification into a single structure, in addition to reducing costs, is necessary to solve structural problems,” said Nikolay Sidorov, general director of the NPF “Future”.
Active work on the consolidation of funds since April is underway in the pension group "Safmar" - NPF "European", "Education and Science" and "Regionfund" should merge into the NPF "Safmar" by the end of this year.
In 2017, the NPF “Trust” will join them.
"The merger of funds will have the effect of strengthening control over risks, operating processes and costs," Safmar's pension group said.
The pause in the merger of funds, which endured "KIT Finance Pension Administrator", can be caused by several reasons, experts say.
Until recently, NPFs could not buy back more than 40% of the volume of infrastructural bonds in which the group was actively located.
After the amendments to the resolution of the Central Bank in March this year on a number of issuers that meet the requirements of the regulator, there are no more such restrictions.
If necessary, the entire issue can be redeemed by one major player," said Yuri Nogin, director of the ACRA ratings group of financial institutions.
Several leaders of the NPF from the top 15 on assets are another possible reason for the pause, calling the separation of spheres of influence and, as a result, personnel appointments in a single fund, which had to be agreed by the owners of the group.
Yesterday, Anatoly Gavrilenko was unavailable for comment.
The request of "Kommersant" in the NPF "Gazfond" was also not answered.
Although the consolidation of funds is a labor-intensive and inexpensive event, at a long distance this decision will be justified.
As noted by the general director of the consulting company "Pension partner" Sergey Okolesnov, the "Pension savings" Gazfond has less outflows, the accession will stabilize the base of other funds of the group.
At the same time, more successful experience of NPF "KIT Finance" and "Promagrofond" in building retail sales of OPS, as well as the use of more modern software will be required.
The requirements of the Central Bank for the processes and personnel of the NPF are constantly growing, so it is not advisable to duplicate the infrastructure on four funds with a single investment policy, said Pavel Mitrofanov, Managing Director for Corporate Ratings of Expert RA.
"The effect of reducing duplicate functions will definitely cover the possible costs of the merger," Mitrofanov said.
