The best Disney movie “Pete and His Dragon” was released in Russia.
Beautiful views of New Zealand, a graceful dragon, a heartwarming story and country songs are enough to once again believe in old-fashioned magic, believes Elena Kravtsun.
The frightened baby was picked up by a dragon, who became a human cub and a tender babysitter, and a devoted friend.
Pete names his friend Elliot, in honor of a puppy from a fairy tale book, plays catch-up with him and falls asleep in a hug.
Six years later, he is no longer distinguished from another clever woodsman, Mowgli, when he is covered and dressed in a thigh bandage.
In this form, Pete is discovered by the red-haired female hunter Grace (Bryce Dallas Howard), while the brigade of Gavin (Carl Urban), her husband's brother, aggressively deforests.
Now she will have to not only believe in the existence of the dragon, but also help to save it.
Pete takes an accelerated course of "being human" surrounded by idyllic Americans who wear cowgirl shirts, a moral code in their hearts and smile more dazzlingly than in any commercial.
No character looks or acts too horrible for the viewer to truly hate or fear him.
Even Gavin, who discovered the hunt for an atypical inhabitant of the forests under his control, is far from an incorrigible villain.
The huge furry dragon also turned out not to be terrible at all, with a good bulldog muzzle, airliner wingspan and the ability to become invisible.
The dragon growls funny, growls, even growls and, fortunately, does not say, but he always wants to stroke, this is advantageously different from all known cinematic dragons.
The visual image of Elliot and his manner of holding provide such a high degree of emotional involvement that in the most tense moments, not only small viewers, but also adults, begin to cry desperately in the three streams.
Surprisingly good and young Oaks Figley in the role of Pete, torn between a possible family and a real friend.
And Robert Redford virtuously gives out a canonical grandfather that every child would be happy to have.
How did director David Lowry manage to make a fantastically cute remake of the forgotten 1977 Disney movie “Dragon of Pete”, mediocre from the nose to the tip of the tail and remembered only by a mix of animation and feature films, and make it the most soulful film of this summer?
No wonder the miracle helped.
In his painting Lowry from the original, in fact, took only two things: the orphan Pete and the dragon.
Overboard were the music numbers and most of the strange jokes.
This good fairy tale reads traits borrowed from "Bambi", "Alien" and many other sweet-hearted children's paintings.
Disney continues to successfully expand the gallery of high-quality remakes of the 21st century.
