The Spiritual Directorate of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the DUM Plenum obliged its imams to deliver Friday sermons only in Tatar, in order to force young Tatars to “learn their native language”.
The administration said that this "in no way infringes" the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
Some mosques in Kazan complain that up to 60% of the parishioners do not understand the Tatar language, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar “will not reach the whole audience.”
Yesterday, the plenary of the DUM of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in the Tatar language.
According to Mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigulin, this should become an incentive for young Tatars to “learn their native language”.
“For those who say it is ‘difficult,’ in every large mosque we intend to organize lessons of the Tatar language absolutely free of charge,” Mr Samigulin promised.
He added that "the decision has already entered into force" and today in all mosques preaching "should be already in the Tatar language".
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
The imam, who does not speak Tatar well enough, “can thoroughly prepare for them.”
DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the Mufti, Friday sermons are conducted exclusively in Tatar.
At the same time in Kazan in a number of mosques previously used mainly Russian language.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnayev Mosque, Zakabanna and Eniler.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, the leadership sets the task that all students should speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no question of any violation of non-Tatar Muslims," Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, explaining that the sermon itself "is not obligatory, the main part of the prayer."
At the same time, the prayer itself will continue to be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian will remain in the mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of displacing the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, for example, Uzbek or Tajik, according to him, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported by the Executive Committee of the World Congress of Tatars (WCC).
The head of the Executive Committee of the VKT Rinat Zakirov told Kommersant: "Mosques are an important part of our national life."
It would be unfortunate if the Tatar language was removed from this sphere.
He noted that preaching only in the Tatar language is "the desire of the imams themselves", but the Executive Committee of the VKT "considers it correct".
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who gave sermons in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the DUM, but they believe that parishioners will have difficulties with understanding the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
They will, of course, be grief-stricken.
“We will have to rebuild,” says the imam of the Burnayev mosque, Farkhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, sermons in Russian are even closer to many Tatars, since "Russian in schools and kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere from the beginning."
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on God.
Allah will show you the way out of this situation,” he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
A lot of foreign students come to us: Africans, Arabs.
“That’s why we switched to Russian for four years,” the imam says.
He believes that in the Tatar language the sermons will "reach to a narrower circle and will not reach the whole audience."
But we will submit to the decision of the Plenary.
The outcome of the sermon will be different.
But time will tell.
“It will be easier for me, for example, because Tatar is my native language,” Galiullin concluded.
Former director of the FSIN put on trial
The Prosecutor’s Office of Moscow has approved the indictment on the criminal case of embezzlement of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Tax Service of Russia.
The former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy will appear before the court, causing damage to the FSIN in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The Metropolitan Prosecutor’s Office sent a criminal case to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia, Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolay Krivolapov, as well as the director of the Federal Penitentiary Information Technology and Communications Center of the Federal Penitentiary Service (FSUE CITOS) Viktor Determinov.
Depending on the role and the degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are charged by the General Prosecutor’s Office of the Criminal Code of Moscow under part 3 of article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, with serious consequences), part 4 of article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using their official position, as part of an organized group, on a particularly large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Part 1 of Article 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and possession of ammunition).
According to the SCR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state treasury budget funds allocated to the FSIN to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
For the theft of budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the enterprise controlled by them, FSUE CITOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", and sold at prices that were overstated several times.
Despite the fact that FSUE CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for the placement of production facilities, allowing to create a complete cycle of production of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between him and FSIN of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, the accounts of the Samara branch of FSUE were more than 2 billion rubles, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. cashed funds received personally Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case in respect of which is allocated to separate proceedings.
Nikolai Kryvolapov, who participated in the machinations, was found of unknown origin of the bullet to the award pistol, which allowed him to bring additional charges.
In this case, which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN filed a claim against the accused for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
