The Russian Copper Company (RMK) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that RMC has undertaken the modernization of one of the oldest and environmentally "dirty" enterprises in the country - the Karabakh copper smelting plant.
The Karabash Coppermelting Plant was founded by an English joint stock company headed by Leslie Urquart in 1910.
In Soviet times, it was an important industrial enterprise for the economy of the country, and it actually provided the vital activity of the whole city.
However, in the 1990s, due to financial problems, production was stopped, which entailed serious social problems in Karabakh.
In 1998, it was decided to resume the operation of the Karabakh copper smelting plant.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabakh plant - environmental.
By the early 2000s, Karabash was already infamous as an ecological disaster zone.
The situation at Karabashmedi began to change in 2004, after the company was transferred to the Russian Copper Company.
The company began to modernize production, which gradually began to reduce the environmental burden on the environment.
This was recently noted by the governor of the Chelyabinsk region, Boris Dubrovsky, who visited Karabashmed in the first days of July.
The head of the Southern Urals called the grandiose changes that have occurred with the enterprise since Karabashmed moved to the RMK group.
The main event for the modernization of Karabashmedi in recent years was the construction of a new sulphuric acid workshop, which allows to capture up to 99.9% of metallurgical gases.
According to the President of the Russian Copper Company Vsevolod Levin, the investment in this project amounted to about 7 billion rubles.
