The WSJ notes that the US usually prefers not to name those who carry out hacking attacks.
The exception is the 2014 hacking of the Sony Entertainment Pictures database, for which the DPRK was officially charged.
Last year, however, Obama issued a decree simplifying sanctions on those who carry out or facilitate cyberattacks.
Initially, it was directed against China, but can also be used against other countries.
The process of deciding on sanctions can be lengthy, the publication writes.
Even if the officials concluded that the hackers acted with the support of Russia, before deciding on the disclosure of information, they will have to weigh the possible consequences.
They will have to determine whether the incident is serious enough to exacerbate tensions in bilateral relations.
