Problems with management in the CENTCOM reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report examines in detail the shortcomings that constantly occurred in 2014 and 2015 in the description and analysis of American actions aimed at training the Iraqi armed forces provided by the Central Command.
While it does not contain conclusive evidence that members of the Obama administration leadership ordered the reports to be falsified, it argues that analysts felt the CENTCOM leadership was forcing them to present a more optimistic view of the threat from the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
“During the first half of 2015, many of the press releases, statements and testimonies of the Central Command in Congress were significantly more optimistic than the actual events,” the report said.
