"Generation protests" in Ethiopia, a longtime U.S. ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally wounded during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of splitting?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a staunch ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country, spreading to more and more of its territory.
Over the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
Human rights defenders said the government’s reaction was brutal.
Witnesses said police officers shot dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage of the protests, supposedly taken late last year or earlier this year, shows security officers beating young people with sticks when they were put their hands against the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights now calls for a thorough investigation.
“It’s always been hard to keep this country from falling apart, and it’s going to be even harder,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project at the International Crisis Research Group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
The U.S. military and intelligence services work closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy – human rights organizations constantly mention government repression – the opposition on the territory of the state was stopped, at the expense of the fact that the dissidents were effectively silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or exiled to remote deserts.
But that could change.
“If people are constantly being repressed and left with no choice but to protest, there will be an uprising,” said Seyum Teshome, a lecturer at the university in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
The generation protested.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use to the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After a widely criticized election last year, the government party and its allies have completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are growing; the struggle for that uncertain, contentious border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the unrest and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, boiling in the depths of the soul for several years, are erupting now.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and the Internet service has become better.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as often happens, especially during protests, many people still find an opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said it was how they organized the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between the Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amharas from the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia flourished in politics and business, exploiting the Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowland areas.
But that's also changing.
“We will act together under a single leadership,” said Mulatto Gemechu, leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the areas of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of the Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 per cent of the population and controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of concern is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at recognising the first signals of discontent and used scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
“The current regime lacks common sense,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalen, appeared out of nowhere and took Meles' place.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a Southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the trust of the security services controlled by the Tigers.
Many fear that this will lead to more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said was an election that the government stalled and then faked the results.
In the ensuing repression, many Protestants were killed, albeit in smaller numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed appreciation to Ethiopia’s leaders for the forward-looking development of infrastructure such as the new long-distance train and significant advances in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this has not stopped the growth of internal discontent with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tigray hatred on social media is becoming overwhelming.
Analysts say the protesters are embarrassing the United States and other Western allies.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it has closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose strength in an already unstable region.
“And it’s going to be hard to get through this tightrope,” Abdi said.
