Clinton earned $10.75 million in 2015 and paid 34.2 percent of the federal tax rate.
Hillary Clinton on Friday unveiled her 2015 tax returns, which showed the Democratic presidential candidate and her husband had $10.75 million in income this year and paid an effective federal tax rate of 34.2 percent.
In 2015, the Clintons received $1 million in charitable contributions, mostly to the Clinton Foundation, former President Bill Clinton received about $5.3 million in speech fees, and the former Secretary of State claimed $3 million in revenue from publisher Simon & Schuster for her book on her tenure at the State Department.
U.S. Senator Tim Kane of Virginia, along with his wife Anna Holton, has released tax returns for 10 years.
In 2015, they paid an effective federal tax rate of 20.3 percent.
“Hillary Clinton and Tim Kane continue to set the standard for financial transparency,” Clinton campaign adviser Jennifer Palmieri said in a statement.
In contrast, Donald Trump hides behind fake excuses and breaks his past promises to make his tax returns public.
It is common for U.S. presidential candidates to publish their tax returns, although the law does not require them to do so.
New York businessman Trump and his lawyers have cited the State Tax Service’s audit as a reason for his refusal to release his tax returns.
“Your move,” Clinton campaign adviser Ian Sams tweeted, referring to the Democratic candidate’s declarations.
