NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to estimates from NASA’s new climate model.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to study the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and carbon-saturated atmosphere, could ever have conditions similar to Earth's.
Scientists had previously assumed that Venus's low rotational speed was due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest modelling suggests that Venus could probably have had a rarefied Earth-like atmosphere and still rotate slowly.
The model also considered the topography of early Venus.
There were probably more arid regions on the planet than on Earth, but once there was enough water and enough geographic variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimer.
"According to the GISS model, Venus' slow rotation replaces its day side with the sun for almost two months at a time," GISS scientist Anthony Del Henio explained in a press release.
This warms the planet’s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella that protects the planet’s surface from much of the sun’s heat.
The result is average climate temperatures, which are surprisingly a few degrees colder than on Earth today.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Although Venus may have once been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen flew away, all that remained was a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect — that is, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
