Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The Kepler space telescope’s latest mission has helped astronomers compile the most comprehensive catalog of the rotational speeds of stars in the Pleiades.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in a cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how periods of rotation correlate with the formation of planets.
“We hope that by comparing our findings with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the star’s mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system,” said Louise Riball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology.
The Pleiades are 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They are spinning as fast as they will never be again.
At their peak rotation speeds, these mature stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have an inhibitory effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its speed of rotation begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable stellar spots — such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotational speeds suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Riball compares stars to dancers: the larger ones make pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades' ballet, we see that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster are usually very light stars," Riball said.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with the speeds of rotation.
"The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both young and old," Riball said.
We still want to know a lot about how, where and why stars slow down and hang their “dance shoes” on the nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiades’ rotational speeds in three new papers that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
