Squeezed between Angola and South Africa, Namibia suffered greatly during the long struggle against apartheid.
However, since gaining independence from South Africa in 1990, the country with a population of 2.4 million has made huge strides, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia's success is that the Government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries take free primary and secondary education for granted, in many poor countries secondary and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce tuition fees to “recover costs”.
However, primary schooling is free in Namibia.
Moreover, since 2015, secondary education has also become free.
The country’s authorities are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases by 97% over the past ten years.
Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is declining in Namibia.
Compared to 1993, the Gini coefficient, a standard indicator of income inequality, fell by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
The poverty rate dropped from 69 per cent in 1993 to less than 30 per cent.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 per day) has also declined, from almost 53 percent to less than 23 percent.
Namibia also has the highest rating of freedom of speech in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country was well ahead of the United States and other wealthy nations.
In addition, the country has a favourable rating – one of the highest in Africa – in the “Corruption Perceptions Index” compiled by human rights defenders from Transparency International.
Even now, with commodity prices falling, Namibia has managed to maintain high growth rates.
At the same time, the debt-to-GDP ratio is around 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the level of debt in the US and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional valuation methods, remains fairly high, at almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high HIV/AIDS prevalence rate, with almost 17 per cent of the population being infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is an upper-middle-income country, but authorities insist that their country is actually a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the difficulties inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated nomad tribes of hunter-gatherers, which in one way or another should be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter of a century ago is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: like any other country in the world, it faces the effects of climate change.
However, Namibia does not think to give up, the country is solving the problems it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities began to create a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
It is noteworthy that rival political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical services not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to medical facilities in the northern regions of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
Namibians realized that the neighbors were not chosen, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, participate in regional medical projects, encourage investment and exchange of students.
In addition, the Namibian government has rightly reasoned that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that the revenues from Namibia’s natural resources need to be invested in infrastructure and production capacity.
They also realize that it would be irresponsible not to seek maximum profit from the sale of a country’s resources, and they are reviewing investment laws and mining contracts to make sure that’s the case.
Transparency is crucial to this process, which is why strong government support for freedom of expression is so important.
As noted by the head of state Hage Geingob, the media often say what he does not like.
But after the struggle for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the freedoms it has gained, the president says.
Not all of Namibia’s key resources are exhaustible.
Some - such as fishing - are renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that begin with serious deficiencies -- racism, colonialism, inequality and low levels of development -- can embark on the path to shared prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many have heard about the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only one burial, known as "Tomb No. 43", was extracted 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the world’s oldest gold may soon move to a seemingly unpretentious beads found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunatsi.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tell Yunatsit is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunatsit of Pazardzhik district.
The beads are a gold stripe rolled into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiyev, the head of the excavations at Tell Yunatsit, dated the find to 4600 BC and stated that it is older than the gold of Varna by at least 200 years.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date from about the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
Technologies that allow to date metal with impeccable accuracy do not currently exist.
How do you know which gold is more ancient?
Obviously, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: "I am quite sure that the gold of the Yunatsi is older than the gold of Varna."
It’s a discovery of extreme importance: it looks like a tiny object, but it’s big enough to occupy a proper place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-examine and more carefully the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the beads with the highest possible accuracy.
The location of the find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunatsi is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Nowadays, Tell Yunatsite is considered the oldest "city" in Europe.
Tell was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
During the following centuries, metal processing in this region developed rapidly, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the national historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: Balkan-Carpathian Metallurgical Province.
In the 5th millennium BC around the centers of metalworking began to emerge settlements of the urban type.
They are now called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunatsit is perhaps the oldest, as artifacts from 4900 BC have been found here.
I would call Tell Yunatsit the prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
“This place is a thousand years older than Sumer,” Boyadzhiev says, referring to the conventional belief that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia – modern Iraq.
It was there that the first cities in the usual sense of the word were formed.
Excavations of the Tell of the Youth have been carried out since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
There is little left of the houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, a "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunatsite is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay figures of birds have been found here.
All birds are depicted at rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of a local cult.
The "Bird City" was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes coming from the northeast.
Nomads had no cities, but they had horses and weapons.
The three-metre-high fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a brutal slaughter: inside the houses were found the remains of old men, women and children with wounds inflicted by combat axes.
New findings and new facts appear every year, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the "Gold of Varna", found relatively recently, in 1972.
Logically, Varna’s golden luxury must have been preceded by something like a tiny gold beads created in the Yunatsit Tell.
